          "body": "One of the psalm's most theologically precise claims is that the wicked are not merely punished from outside — they are destroyed by the logic of their own schemes. 'The nations have sunk down in the pit which they have made; in the net which they hid, their own foot has been caught' (9:15). This is the doctrine of retributive self-destruction — the trap becomes the trap-setter's tomb. Verse 16 presses the point: 'The wicked is snared in the work of his own hands.' God does not need to introduce alien instruments of judgment; He allows the sinner's own devices to execute His sentence. This pattern runs throughout Scripture: Haman is hanged on the gallows he built for Mordecai (Esther 7:10); the men who threw Daniel's friends into the furnace are destroyed by the fire they stoked (Daniel 3:22); Saul of Tarsus is blinded by the light of the One he persecuted. The Higgaion-Selah of verse 16 is a double command to pause here and meditate — this is not a passing observation but a deep theological truth about the shape of history."
