          "title": "The closing petition — mortal man before the eternal Judge (9:19-20)",
          "body": "The psalm closes not with resolution but with renewed petition: 'Arise, O Lord, do not let man prevail; let the nations be judged before You. Put them in fear, O Lord; let the nations know that they are but men' (9:19-20). The Hebrew word for 'man' here is enosh — not adam (the image-bearer) but enosh (the mortal, the frail, the merely human). The psalm's closing argument is not primarily about what the nations have done but about what they are — mortal creatures acting as though they are beyond accountability. The petition is that the nations would know their true identity: finite, transient creatures answerable to the infinite Judge. This is the anti-idolatry conclusion of the psalm: national power, military might, and geopolitical dominance are all enosh — mere man, mortal, no more permanent than the grass of Psalm 90. The psalm that began with David thanking God with all his heart ends with the nations being called to face a court that will settle every account. The reader who has followed the psalm from verse 1 to verse 20 has been moved from private praise to cosmic petition — a movement that is itself a model of prayer."
