        "excerpt": "I will give thanks to the Lord with all my heart; I will tell of all Your wonders.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with four consecutive declarations beginning 'I will' — yadah (give thanks), saphar (tell/recount), samach (be glad), zamar (sing praise). This quadruple volition is not the spontaneous overflow of a comfortable life; it is the deliberate commitment of a will that has chosen its posture before the facts are fully resolved. The enemy has not yet fully perished when David begins to praise — the verb tenses in verse 3 use temporal clauses ('when my enemies turn back') suggesting the praise precedes the final outcome.\n\nThe theological logic is important. David praises not because the threat is over but because he has reckoned the Judge's throne to be more stable than the enemy's power. This is what Charles Spurgeon called 'the triumph of faith over sense' — not denying the reality of the enemy but refusing to let the enemy set the emotional register. The 'all my heart' (lev) of verse 1 signals totality: no compartmentalized gratitude, no faith in one register and anxiety in another.\n\nVerses 3-6 recount past deliverances in rapid, stacked perfects: You have maintained, You have sat, You have rebuked, You have destroyed, You have blotted out, You have uprooted. The grammatical pile-up mirrors the theological conviction — God's interventions are not isolated events but a consistent pattern. The enemy has come to 'perpetual ruins' (netsach chorbah, 9:6), and even the memory of the enemy has perished (zekher avad). This is the most radical form of divine judgment: not merely military defeat but ontological erasure. The enemy sought to eliminate Israel; God eliminates the enemy's name from history itself.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yadah* (give thanks, 9:1) — the hiphil stem connotes public, confessional acknowledgment, not merely private sentiment. *Pala* (wonders, 9:1) — miraculous, extraordinary acts that exceed human capacity. *Netsach* (perpetual/forever, 9:6) — used of both the enemy's ruin (9:6) and of what 'will not always be' for the needy (9:18); the word's range covers both permanent destruction and temporary affliction, depending on context."
