        "excerpt": "But the Lord abides forever; He has established His throne for judgment, and He will judge the world in righteousness.",
        "body": "The hinge of the entire psalm is the word 'but' (NASB) — the great adversative that turns from the description of perishing enemies to the declaration of the eternal Lord. Everything in the psalm that follows draws its stability from this pivot. The enemy's name is blotted out forever (9:5-6); by contrast, the Lord abides (yashav, literally 'sits') forever. The same posture of sitting — enthroned, at rest, immovable — appears in verse 4 (God sitting on His throne) and again here (God sitting forever). The throne does not shift; the Judge does not vacate.\n\nVerses 7-8 expand the jurisdiction from David's personal case to global scope: 'He will judge the world in righteousness; He will execute judgment for the peoples with equity.' The Hebrew tsedeq (righteousness) and meshar (equity, uprightness) are both legal-ethical terms — this is not God showing favoritism but God applying His perfectly consistent standard to all nations. John Calvin (Commentary on the Psalms) observes that this universalism is precisely the comfort for the believer: a God who judges only His friends' enemies is a partisan; a God who judges all peoples with equity is a guarantee of actual justice.\n\nVerses 9-10 bring the cosmic back to the personal: 'The Lord also will be a stronghold for the oppressed, a stronghold in times of trouble; and those who know Your name will put their trust in You, for You, O Lord, have not forsaken those who seek You.' The word misgav (stronghold/refuge) appears twice in verse 9 — the repetition is not redundancy but intensity. God is the refuge in the abstract category (for the oppressed) and in the specific circumstance (in times of trouble). The bridge between the eternal Judge and the personal refugee is the phrase 'those who know Your name' — the shem of verse 10 is God's revealed character, not merely His title. Trusting God is grounded in knowing who God is, which is why the psalm has spent verses 7-8 describing Him with such precision.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Misgav* (stronghold, 9:9) — a high, inaccessible place; used of mountain fortresses. *Yada* (know, 9:10) — intimate, relational knowledge, not merely intellectual acquaintance (the same verb used of marital intimacy in Genesis 4:1). *Batach* (trust, 9:10) — to lean upon, to rest one's weight on; implies vulnerability and complete reliance."
