        "body": "The psalm now drops into its most personal register. After the soaring theological claims of 9:7-12, the reader arrives at raw petition: 'Be gracious to me (chanan), O Lord; see my affliction.' Chanan (be gracious) is the cry of one who has no legal claim — it does not appeal to the Judge's verdict but to the Judge's mercy. David knows that the affliction is real, that those who hate him have pressed him to the gates of death (shaar mavet), and that only an act of divine grace can reverse his trajectory.\n\nBut the petition is not self-focused. Its stated purpose is doxological: 'that I may tell of all Your praises, that in the gates of the daughter of Zion I may rejoice in Your salvation.' The reason David wants to be delivered from death's gates is not primarily survival — it is testimony. He wants to be moved from one gate to another: from the gate of death to the gates of Zion, from the threshold of the grave to the entrance of the praising community. This purpose-clause is one of the most revealing statements in the Psalter about the ultimate aim of divine rescue: not merely the prolongation of biological life but the amplification of doxological witness.\n\nThis structure — petition grounded in doxological purpose — appears repeatedly in the Psalms (cf. Psalm 22:22-25; 40:3; 71:14-18) and is a persistent feature of Old Testament prayer. It is also deeply Christological. The Son of God cried from a darker version of 'the gates of death' (Matthew 27:46, quoting Psalm 22:1) and was raised not merely to live but to be declared Lord and to be proclaimed among the nations (Romans 1:4; 10:9-13). Psalm 9:13-14 is a biographical sample of the pattern the incarnation will replay on a cosmic scale.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chanan* (be gracious, 9:13) — unmerited favor, the gracious inclination of a superior toward an inferior; always implies the giver's freedom, never the recipient's entitlement. *Shaar mavet* (gates of death, 9:13) — the entrance to Sheol; the metaphor of gates underscores death as a realm with a threshold, not a void. *Yeshuah* (salvation, 9:14) — deliverance, rescue, the saving act of God; same root as the name Jesus (Yeshua)."
