        "body": "Verses 15-18 resume the third-person narrative of divine justice begun in 9:3-6 and extend it with the most precise description of retributive self-destruction in the psalm. The nations have not merely been defeated — they have been destroyed by their own instruments. The pit they excavated to trap the afflicted has swallowed them; the net they spread for others has caught their own feet (9:15). Verse 16 interprets this: 'The Lord has made Himself known; He has executed judgment. In the work of his own hands the wicked is snared.' God's self-revelation (yada, made Himself known) happens through the mechanism of justice — His character is displayed precisely in the way He allows sinful schemes to collapse inward.\n\nThe double marker — Higgaion Selah — at verse 16 commands an extended pause. This is the only such double rubric in the Psalter, marking the verse as demanding sustained meditation. The reader is told: stop here. Think carefully about what it means that the Judge makes Himself known by allowing the wicked to be snared in their own work. This is not a peripheral observation but the theological center of the psalm's retributive argument.\n\nVerse 17 extends the retribution to its ultimate horizon: 'The wicked will return to Sheol, even all the nations who forget God.' The category 'nations who forget God' (goy shakheach elohim) defines the condemned not by what they have done so much as by what they have neglected: forgetting. This is significant — it means the judgment of nations is not merely punitive for great crimes but responsive to a fundamental orientation of the will away from God. Verse 18 provides the antithesis: 'For the needy will not always be forgotten, nor the hope of the afflicted perish forever.' The needy will not share the fate of those who forget God — because God, unlike the nations, does not forget.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Higgaion* (9:16) — likely 'meditation' or 'solemn sound'; combined with Selah uniquely here. *Shakheach elohim* (forget God, 9:17) — the participle form suggests a settled disposition of forgetting, not a momentary lapse. *Tiqvah* (hope, 9:18) — expectation, the thread of confidence stretched toward the future; same word used in Jeremiah 29:11 ('plans to give you a future and a hope')."
